Combinatorial Game Theory (CGT)

Two-player perfect-information games with no randomness and players alternate moves until a terminal position.

Outcome is win/lose (sometimes draw) and the game must eventually terminate.

Examples: Chess, Tic-Tac-Toe, Game of Nim.

Two types:

Impartial games: both players have the same set of moves from any position (e.g., Nim).

Partisan games: players have different moves (e.g., Chess). {one player always moves with only one color}

Impartial games are easier to analyze and use tools like Sprague–Grundy theorem. 


Game of Nim

Problem:

Given n piles of stones. Each turn a player removes ≥1 stones from a single pile. Players alternate; whoever takes the last stone wins.

Key Observation (Nim-Sum):

Compute XOR of all piles.

If NimSum = 0 → first player loses (optimal play)

If NimSum ≠ 0 → first player can force a win.

Winning Move:
Reduce some pile p to p ^ NimSum so the new XOR becomes 0.

Code

bool firstPlayerWins(vector<int>& piles) {
    int nim = 0;
    for (int p : piles) nim ^= p;
    return nim != 0;
}

Optimal Move

pair<int,int> move(vector<int>& piles) {
    int nim = 0;
    for (int p : piles) nim ^= p;

    for (int i = 0; i < piles.size(); i++) {
        int target = piles[i] ^ nim;
        if (target < piles[i])
            return {i, piles[i] - target}; // remove stones
    }
    return {-1,-1}; // losing position
}

1. Grundy Numbers (Game State Value)

A Grundy Number (G) represents the value of a game state in an impartial game.

Definition

G(state) = mex( Grundy(all possible next states) )

Special case:

If no moves possible → G = 0

Meaning:

G = 0 → losing position

G ≠ 0 → winning position

2. Mex (Minimum Excluded)

Mex(S) = smallest non-negative integer not in S

Examples:

mex{0,1,2} = 3
mex{1,2,3} = 0
mex{0,2,3} = 1



Mex essentially finds the first missing number.

3. How Grundy Numbers Are Computed

General template:

G(state) = mex{ G(next_state1), G(next_state2), ... }

Algorithm:

List all possible moves

Compute Grundy for resulting states

Take mex

4. Example 1 — Take Any Stones (Classic Nim)

Moves: remove 1..n stones

Transitions:

n → n-1, n-2, ..., 0

So:

G(n) = mex{ G(0), G(1), ... G(n-1) }

Result:

G(n) = n

Example:

G(0) = 0
G(1) = mex{0} = 1
G(2) = mex{0,1} = 2
G(3) = mex{0,1,2} = 3

This explains why Nim uses XOR.

5. Example 2 — Remove Only 1,2,3 Stones

Moves:

n → n-1, n-2, n-3

Recurrence:

G(n) = mex{ G(n-1), G(n-2), G(n-3) }

Values:

n : 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7 ...
G : 0 1 2 3 0 1 2 3 ...

Pattern:

G(n) = n % 4

7. Sprague-Grundy Theorem (Most Important Idea)

Every impartial game can be converted to equivalent Nim piles.

If the game has multiple independent subgames:

Grundy_total = G1 ⊕ G2 ⊕ ... ⊕ Gn

Where:

Gi = Grundy number of subgame i

Decision rule:

Grundy_total = 0 → losing state
Grundy_total ≠ 0 → winning state
8. Example

Piles:

3,4,5

For "remove up to 3":

G(3)=3
G(4)=0
G(5)=1

Compute XOR:

3 ⊕ 0 ⊕ 1 = 2 ≠ 0

First player wins.

