Problem: Alice and Bob are playing a game with candy baskets. Initially, there are N baskets, and the i-th basket has candies_in_basket_i candies and a special number candies_limit_i. 
The game starts with Alice, and they take turns. On each turn, the player picks a basket and takes away some candies. 
If the player chooses the i-th basket and there are candies_left_in_basket_i candies, they must take between 1 and floor(candies_left_in_basket_i / candies_limit_i) candies. 
The player who can't make a move (because all baskets are empty or they can't take the required number of candies) loses the game. 
Both Alice and Bob play perfectly, so they always make the best possible moves. Your task is to determine who will win the game, assuming both play optimally.


This is a generalised nim game 

1. Break the game into subgames

Each basket behaves independently.

So the full game is a composite game of N subgames.

By the Sprague–Grundy theorem:

winner depends on XOR of Grundy numbers of all baskets

If

G1 ^ G2 ^ ... ^ GN ≠ 0 → Alice wins
G1 ^ G2 ^ ... ^ GN = 0 → Bob wins

2. Understand a single basket

Basket i:

candies = x
limit = k

Allowed move:

remove 1 ... floor(x / k)

So transitions are:

x → x-1
x → x-2
...
x → x-floor(x/k)

This is exactly an impartial game, so we compute

G(x) = mex{ G(x-1), G(x-2), ..., G(x-floor(x/k)) }

int grundy(int x, int k, vector<int>& dp) {
    if (x == 0) return 0;
    if (dp[x] != -1) return dp[x];

    unordered_set<int> s;

    int limit = x / k;

    for (int take = 1; take <= limit; take++)
        s.insert(grundy(x - take, k, dp));

    int g = 0;
    while (s.count(g)) g++;

    return dp[x] = g;
}

